# How to Install NGINX on Ubuntu Using EC2 User Data Script

## Step by Step with Example

User Data in EC2 allows you to run commands automatically when instance starts.

We will:

✅ Launch Ubuntu EC2
✅ Install NGINX automatically
✅ Start NGINX service
✅ Open website in browser

---

# 🔹 What is User Data?

When EC2 instance launches, AWS runs commands inside:

```text id="lgfcde"
User Data Script
```

Automatically on first boot.

Used for:

✅ Install software
✅ Configure server
✅ Deploy application
✅ Start services

---

# 🔹 Final Goal

After EC2 launches:

```text id="k0ik3d"
Ubuntu EC2
→ NGINX installed automatically
→ Website accessible from browser
```

---

# 🔹 Step 1: Open AWS EC2 Console

Go to:

AWS Console → EC2 → Instances

Click:

```text id="i7o9tx"
Launch Instance
```

---

# 🔹 Step 2: Configure Instance

## Name

Example:

```text id="hfz3ij"
nginx-server
```

---

## AMI

Choose:

```text id="qok1su"
Ubuntu Server 24.04 LTS
```

---

## Instance Type

```text id="4jts3u"
t2.micro
```

(Free tier eligible)

---

## Key Pair

Choose existing key OR create new one.

Example:

```text id="ijrbzi"
my-key.pem
```

Download key.

---

# 🔹 Step 3: Configure Security Group

Allow:

| Type | Port |
| ---- | ---- |
| SSH  | 22   |
| HTTP | 80   |

Very important.

---

# 🔹 Step 4: Add User Data Script

Scroll to:

```text id="1sw8sz"
Advanced Details
```

Find:

```text id="cw4uws"
User Data
```

Paste script:

```bash id="0x4hmu"
#!/bin/bash

apt update -y
apt install nginx -y

systemctl start nginx
systemctl enable nginx

echo "<h1>NGINX Installed Using User Data</h1>" > /var/www/html/index.html
```

---

# 🔹 What This Script Does

## Line 1

```bash id="2h5wsf"
#!/bin/bash
```

Tells Linux to use bash shell.

---

## Update Packages

```bash id="fjlwmr"
apt update -y
```

Updates Ubuntu package list.

---

## Install NGINX

```bash id="t5t1q9"
apt install nginx -y
```

Installs NGINX automatically.

---

## Start Service

```bash id="u8t59k"
systemctl start nginx
```

Starts web server.

---

## Enable on Boot

```bash id="l0b5va"
systemctl enable nginx
```

NGINX auto starts after reboot.

---

## Create Website

```bash id="8cft7y"
echo "<h1>NGINX Installed Using User Data</h1>" > /var/www/html/index.html
```

Creates custom HTML page.

---

# 🔹 Step 5: Launch Instance

Click:

```text id="b9y9zn"
Launch Instance
```

Wait 1–2 minutes.

---

# 🔹 Step 6: Open Website

Copy EC2 public IP:

Example:

```text id="c8l2lp"
http://54.xx.xx.xx
```

Browser output:

```text id="zt8pku"
NGINX Installed Using User Data
```

Success ✅

---

# 🔹 Step 7: Verify Using SSH

Connect:

```bash id="0lf0w2"
ssh -i my-key.pem ubuntu@PUBLIC-IP
```

Check NGINX:

```bash id="mk33s8"
systemctl status nginx
```

---

# 🔹 Check User Data Logs

If script fails:

```bash id="uhvnnf"
cat /var/log/cloud-init-output.log
```

Very important for troubleshooting.

